<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12144h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12144h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12144h"> 144(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> taxgatherers / in orders to escape / charge</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Sous les r&egrave;gnes de Diocl&eacute;tien et de Constantin (284-337), pour r&eacute;parer les d&eacute;sordres du si&egrave;cle pr&eacute;c&eacute;dent, on demanda &agrave; l&apos;imp&ocirc;t tout ce qu&apos;il pouvait rendre.&hellip; La classe moyenne devenait donc la partie imposable de l&apos;empire. Tout propri&eacute;taire d&apos;au moins treize acres de terre &eacute;tait honor&eacute; du titre de d&eacute;curion. Il devenait, du coup, la chose du fisc.&hellip; Il demeurait possible, cependant, de passer &agrave; travers les mailles du r&eacute;seau: c&apos;&eacute;tait de se faire homme d&apos;&Eacute;glise; on &eacute;chappait de la sorte aux devoirs civils de la charge de d&eacute;curion. Est-ce pour cela que nous trouvons Potitus, pr&ecirc;tre et Calpurnius, diacre? <br><font color="green">[29-31: Under the reigns of Diocletian and of Constantine (284-327), in order to repair the disorders of the preceding century, people were taxed to the utmost &hellip; the middle-class became the taxable part of the Empire. Every owner of at least thirteen acres was honoured by the name of decurion, and he thus became the prey of the fisc &hellip; There was, however, one way of escaping from the toils, which was to take Orders; in this way one might avoid the civil duties of the decurion&apos;s office. Was it not probably for this reason that we find Potitus a priest and Calpurnius a deacon?]</font> <small> Riguet, Abb&eacute; <a name="RTSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RTSP"><cite title="source">Saint Patrice</cite></a> (1911) 35</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
